      <h4>
        üíª Example: Morphological Analysis in Action
      </h4>
      <p>
        <strong>
          Word:
        </strong>
        "unfriendliness"
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>
          Step-by-step breakdown:
        </strong>
      </p>
      <div className="example-steps">
        <div className="step">
          Identify the root: "friend" (noun, meaning companion)
        </div>
        <div className="step">
          Add derivational suffix "-ly": "friendly" (adjective, meaning having the characteristics of a friend)
        </div>
        <div className="step">
          Add derivational prefix "un-": "unfriendly" (adjective, meaning not friendly)
        </div>
        <div className="step">
          Add derivational suffix "-ness": "unfriendliness" (noun, meaning the state of being unfriendly)
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        <strong>
          Result:
        </strong>
        4 morphemes total (1 root + 3 affixes), word class changed from noun ‚Üí adjective ‚Üí adjective ‚Üí noun
      </p>
    </div>
    <h3 className="subsection-title">
      ‚ö†Ô∏è Common Misconceptions
    </h3>
    <div className="alert alert-danger">
      <strong>
        Misconception #1:
      </strong>
      "Morphemes are the same as syllables."
      <p>
        <strong>
          Reality:
        </strong>
        Morphemes are units of
        <em>
          meaning
        </em>
        , while syllables are units of
        <em>
          sound
        </em>
        . The word "cats" has one syllable but two morphemes (cat + -s). Conversely, "banana" has three syllables (ba-na-na) but only one morpheme.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div className="alert alert-danger">
      <strong>
        Misconception #2:
      </strong>
      "All prefixes and suffixes are the same type."
      <p>
        <strong>
          Reality:
        </strong>
        Affixes serve different functions. Derivational affixes create new words and can change word class (happy ‚Üí happiness), while inflectional affixes only add grammatical information and never change word class (cat ‚Üí cats).
      </p>
    </div>
    <div className="alert alert-danger">
      <strong>
        Misconception #3:
      </strong>
      "Longer words always have more morphemes."
      <p>
        <strong>
          Reality:
        </strong>
        Word length doesn't determine morpheme count. "Antidisestablishmentarianism" has 6 morphemes despite being 28 letters, while "strengths" has only 2 morphemes (strong + -th + -s = actually 3: strong + -th + -s) despite being 8 letters.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div className="alert alert-danger">
      <strong>
        Misconception #4:
      </strong>
      "Every word must contain at least one bound morpheme."
      <p>
        <strong>
          Reality:
        </strong>
        Many words consist entirely of free morphemes. Simple words like "cat," "run," "blue," and "book" are single free morphemes with no bound morphemes attached.
      </p>
    </div>
